tionRevisions","id":"55943","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55943"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn otherwise well 45-year-old man goes to see his general practitioner after an episode of epigastric pain which lasted four hours and then resolved spontaneously. There is nothing else to be gleaned from the history and the physical examination is unremarkable. A CT scan is performed and this is normal apart from an enhancing, homogenous 5 cm mass in the region of the left adrenal gland. The margins are well defined and the lesion appears to be encapsulated. A more detailed history and physical examination does not provide any further information.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["No further action","CT-guided needle biopsy","MRI scan","Repeat CT in six months","Adrenal hormone assays"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIncidental findings on CT scans are relatively common, being found in some 20 - 40% of such investigations. Adrenal adenomas are often identified in this manner and most are benign and non-functioning. In the adult population the prevalence of adrenal incidentaloma varies between 1 - 6%. and the prevalence is increasing with the expanding use of increasingly sophisticated imaging technology.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhen found, there must be a structured approach to their management. This will start with a careful history and examination to determine if there is any evidence of excess adrenal hormone active or suggestion of malignancy. This will be followed by a biochemical evaluation:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Edexamethasone suppression test\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E24-hour urinary metanephrines and catecholamines\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf hypertensive: \u2013 plasma aldosterone to plasma renal activity ratio\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EProvided these tests are negative, no further immediate action needs to be taken, except if the adrenal mass is greater than 4 cm or has radiological suspicions of malignancy. The risk of malignancy increases in larger tumours. Suspicious features include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u0026gt;10 Hounsfield units on CT\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECT contrast washout \u0026lt;40-60%\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMRI hyperintense on T2 imaging or no signal loss on chemical-shift analysis\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMalignant tumours often have a characteristic appearance on CT (increased unenhanced CT attenuation), but these observations are not absolute. Based on size alone, this patient needs to be referred for an adrenalectomy. Consideration must also be given to the possibilities of increased hormonal activity (Cushing\u0027s syndrome, pheochromocytoma, Conn\u0027s syndrome) and appropriate endocrine investigations and \u003Cstrong\u003Eadrenal hormone assays\u003C/strong\u003E performed to exclude these conditions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere is no place for \u003Cstrong\u003ECT-guided needle biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E in this case and sufficient information has been gained from the CT scan making a \u003Cstrong\u003EMRI scan\u003C/strong\u003E unnecessary.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe small, asymptomatic adenoma can usually be left well alone, with repeated imaging if there are indeterminate features and biochemical evaluation at regular intervals.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Incidental findings of adrenal lesions are a relatively common occurrence on cross sectional radiology."],"references":["Jason DS, Oltmann SC. Evaluation of an Adrenal Incidentaloma. Surg Clin N Am. 2019; 99:721-29.","kebebew E. Adrenal Incidentaloma. N Engl J Med 2021; 384:1542-51."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41492"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"392"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41492","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/41492"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-18T20:27:46+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-18T20:28:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"392"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55943"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagG